cter in relation to specific legal cases and doctrines, including the right to silence, libel and privacyIncludes new work on Anthony Trollope’s topical and editorial interest in libel Covers the relationship between libel, the development of privacy rights and emerging modernist aestheticsPresents a transatlantic approach to select works and issues, including the right to silence and privacy Why would Hawthorne and Eliot grant their fallen women an anachronistic right to silence that could only worsen their punishment? Why did Bronte and Gaskell find gossip such a useful source of information when lawyers excluded it as hearsay? How did Trollope’s work as an editor influence his preoccupation throughout his novels with libel?Drawing on a range of primary sources including novels, Victorian periodical literature, legislative debate, case law, and legal treatise, Cathrine O. Frank traces the ways conventions of literary characterisation mingled with character-centred legal developments to produce a jurisprudential theory of character that extends beyond the legal profession. She explores how key categories and representational strategies for imagining individual personhood also defined communities and mediated relations within them, in life and in fiction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCharacter in literature. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and cricitism. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLaw and literaturezGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaw in literature. 4aLaw. 7aLAW / Jurisprudence.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311078039040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147448572240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474485722423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9